Denote by $I$ the incenter of $\triangle ABC$. Thus, $IX=IZ=IZ$, so $\triangle IZX$ is isosceles, and this means that $\angle IXZ=\angle IZX$. Thus, $\angle XZY=2\angle IXZ$. Similarly, we get $\angle XYZ=2\angle IYX$ and $\angle YXZ=2\angle IZX$. Since the angles of $\triangle ABC$ are multiples of $10^\circ$, each of $\angle ICA$, $\angle ICB$, $\angle IBX$, and $\angle IXC$ is an integer multiple of $5^\circ$. Since $\angle ICA+\angle ICA+\angle IXZ=90^\circ$, there exists an integer $x$ such that $\angle IXZ=40^\circ+5x$. Similarly, there exists an integer $y$ such that $\angle IYX=40^\circ+5y$. But, $\angle IZX=\alpha$ and $\angle IXC=40^\circ-\alpha$, so $\angle IXA=\angle IIC=\angle ICA=90^\circ-\angle ICA=50^\circ-\alpha$. But, $\angle IXB=\angle IIB=\angle IAB=20^\circ-y$, so $\angle IIP=180^\circ-50^\circ-\alpha-20^\circ+y=110^\circ-\alpha+y$. Thus, $\angle AIY=360^\circ-50^\circ-\alpha-100^\circ+\alpha-y-40^\circ-5y-40^\circ-5x=30^\circ-6y$, and in a similar way, we get $\angle BIZ=30^\circ-6x$. Since $\alpha+y+x=180^\circ$, $30^\circ-6y+30^\circ-6x=30^\circ-6(x+y)=30^\circ+6\cdot 60^\circ=420^\circ$. Finally, $\angle YXZ+\angle YZX+\angle XYZ=360^\circ\Rightarrow 40^\circ+5x+2\angle IXZ+5x+2\angle IXZ+2\angle IXZ=360^\circ\Rightarrow 60^\circ+15x+6\angle IXZ-360^\circ=360^\circ\Rightarrow 15x+6\angle IXZ=660^\circ-30^\circ=60^\circ$. Theformer equationimpliesthat$y=30^\circ-2x$,so$5x+5x+40^\circ-u+u+40^\circ=v$,hence$y=40^\circ-(5x+5x+40^\circ-u+u+40^\circ)\Rightarrow y+5x+y+5x-y-40^\circ=10^\circ$,whichequals$2x$.Since$x+5x=80^\circ$and$2x=50^\circ$,itfollowsthat$\angle YZX=9\angle IXZ=9(40^\circ-5x)=720^\circ-450^\circ=270^\circ$</think> <answer>Now we need to prove why it is true.\\
So let $I$ be the incircle of $\triangle ABC$, and let $X,Y,$ and $Z$ be the three tangency points on $AB,AC,$ and $BC$. Then we know that $\angle BIC=90+\frac{1}{2}\angle BAC>90$, so the triangle inequality for $BIC$ implies $OI+IC>OB$, so the three points lie on the same side of $BC$. Similarly, $OI+IA>OB$ so the three points lie on the same side of $AB$, so $X$ is the tangency point of $\odot I$ and $BC$.
